In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims April as National Cancer Control Month. He highlights the impact of cancer as one of the leading causes of death in the United States, taking over half a million lives annually. However, he also emphasizes the progress being made in managing and understanding cancer, with rates of new cases and deaths declining in recent years.

President Obama urges Americans to renew their commitment to combat this disease by raising awareness and supporting the development of life-saving treatments. He encourages individuals to engage in preventive care by discussing it with a health professional, getting regular check-ups and screenings, and making lifestyle changes such as limiting sun exposure, alcohol consumption, and tobacco use, as well as exercising regularly and maintaining a nutritious diet.

The President acknowledges the disparities that exist between races, ethnicities, and incomes regarding cancer survival rates and emphasizes the role of community cancer centers in closing these gaps and providing hope to underserved citizens.

President Obama shares his personal experience of losing a loved one to cancer and expresses his determination to triumph over this devastating illness. He references a joint resolution by the Congress of the United States, approved in 1938, requesting the President to issue an annual proclamation declaring April as "Cancer Control Month."

In conclusion, President Obama calls upon citizens, government agencies, organizations, healthcare providers, and research institutions to raise cancer awareness and continue helping Americans live longer and healthier lives.